"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448370","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-04","<p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The Intellectual Property Office has committed to provision of £1.5m funding for the Police Intellectual Property Crime Unit in 2016-17. Funding beyond that period is still to be determined.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-02-04T17:38:46.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448370/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448370/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448370/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-27","Police Intellectual Property Crime Unit: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what his Department's planned expenditure on the Police Intellectual Property Crime Unit is for (a) 2016-17, (b) 2017-18, (c) 2018-19 and (d) 2019-20.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","24521"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448371","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-04","<p>The Police Intellectual Property Crime Unit is funded by the Intellectual Property Office, but is considered operationally independent, and is fully managed by the City of London Police. Future staffing levels will be a matter for the City of London Police to determine in the light of the unit’s workload and requirements.</p><p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-02-04T17:40:15.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448371/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448371/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448371/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-27","Police Intellectual Property Crime Unit: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what estimate his Department has made of how many full time police officers will work in the Police Intellectual Property Crime Unit in (a) 2016-17, (b) 2017-18, (c) 2018-19 and (d) 2019-20.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","24522"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448372","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-19","<p>The current (2015-16) established strength for the unit is;</p><p>0.5 x Detective Chief Inspector</p><p>1 x Detective Inspector</p><p>2 x Detective Sergeant</p><p>2 x Police Staff Investigator</p><p>2 x Analyst</p><p>2 x Researcher</p><p>1 x Communications officer</p><p> </p><p>We do not have historical figures for staff numbers available, but the team has been of the same approximate size since inception.</p><p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-02-19T10:24:45.753Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448372/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448372/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448372/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-27","Police Intellectual Property Crime Unit: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many full-time police officers worked in the Police Intellectual Property Crime Unit in (a) 2013-14, (b) 2014-15 and (c) 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","24523"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448373","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-04","<p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Figures for the years in question are as follows;</p><p>(a) 2013-14, 16 arrests, 2 cautions</p><p>(b) 2014-15, 33 arrests, 11 cautions</p><p>(c) 2015-16, 13 arrests, 1 caution, 1 conviction</p><p> </p><p>Securing convictions is not the sole aim of the unit. Equally important in the fight against IP crime is the Unit’s work on taking down infringing websites and pursuing broader disruptive activity.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-02-04T17:43:10.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448373/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448373/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448373/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-27","Police Intellectual Property Crime Unit: Convictions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many successful convictions were secured by the Police Intellectual Property Crime Unit in (a) 2013-14, (b) 2014-15 and (c) 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","24524"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448374","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-07","<p>The Intellectual Property Office has funded the Police Intellectual Property Crime Unit as follows;</p><p> </p><p>(a) 2013-14 £0.975m</p><p>(b) 2014-15 £1.423m</p><p>(c) 2015-16 £0.677m billed to September 2015 (funding period still ongoing)</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-02-07T10:26:45.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448374/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448374/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448374/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-27","Police Intellectual Property Crime Unit: Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what his Department's spending on the Police Intellectual Property Crime Unit was in (a) 2013-14, (b) 2014-15 and (c) 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","24525"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448375","Home Office","false","2016-02-04","<p>The Harm-Benefit Analysis (HBA) is undertaken, on behalf of the Secretary of State, by the Animals in Science Regulation Unit inspectors, all of whom are veterinary or medically qualified and trained in assessing research proposals. The HBA is the process of considering a research proposal to make a judgement whether the likely harms that the animals will experience are justified by the likely benefits. Under section 18 of the Animals (Scientific Procedures) Act 1986, inspectors advise the Secretary of State who decides whether and on what terms a project licence should be granted.</p><p>The number of project licences which were recommended for grant by the Animals in Science Regulation Unit inspectors between 2012 and 2015 are shown in table 1, column (c).</p><p>The Secretary of State has not rejected any of the recommendations for granting project licences made by the Animals in Science Regulation Unit inspectors between 2012 and 2015.</p><p>The Home Office does not keep records of applications that have been rejected or withdrawn at the concept or drafting stage [24507]. The Home Office does not keep records of which applications were withdrawn as a result of advice from the Animals in Science Regulation Unit inspectors.</p><p>The Home Office refers project licence applications to both the Animals in Science Committee and external independent assessors for critical review. The number of project licences referred to both is given in Table 1 columns (a) and (b) respectively for the years 2012-15.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>(a) Project licence applications referred to the Animals in Science Committee<strong>[1]</strong></strong></p></td><td><p><strong>(b) Project licence applications referred to independent assessors</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>(c) Project licences granted</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>9</p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>626</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>604</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>474</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>577</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p>[1] Prior to 2013 the independent advisory body was entitled the ‘Animals Procedures Committee’</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","24507 ; 24508 ; 24509 ; 24510","2016-02-04T15:22:55.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448375/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448375/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/448375/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-01-27","Animal Experiments: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to Advice Note: 05/2015, paragraph 9 of the Harm-Benefit Analysis Process, how many project licences applications under the Animals (Scientific Procedures) Act 1986 were recommended by the Animals and Science Regulation Unit in each year since 2012.","false","Biography information for Angela Smith","Penistone and Stocksbridge","Angela Smith","24519"
