"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447813","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-29","<p>We will publish a full evaluation of the In-Work Progression Randomised Control Trial, which will include both in-house and externally commissioned research.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-01-29T09:33:45.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447813/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447813/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447813/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-01-26","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether he plans to commission and publish an independent evaluation of the universal credit in-work conditionality pilots.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","24116"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447814","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-29","<p>The information requested in the Rt. Hon Member’s letter was sent to the Work and Pensions Select Committee on Friday 29 January 2016.</p><br /> <br />","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-01-29T13:27:53.193Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447814/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447814/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447814/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-01-26","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, when he plans to reply to the letter from the hon. Member for Birkenhead to him dated 19 January 2016 on the state pension.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","24182"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447815","Department for Work and Pensions","true","2016-01-29","<p>There are no breakdowns available by income level either for DC personal pensions or for DC workplace pensions.</p><p>There is also no breakdown available by age for DC personal pensions, but data on the distribution of employee contribution rates to workplace DC schemes, by age, can be found within Reference Table 5.1 of the Annual Survey of Hours and Earnings (ASHE) 2014 publication available here: <del class="ministerial"><a href="http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/publications/re-reference-tables.html?edition=tcm%3A77-400776" target="_blank">http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/publications/re-reference-tables.html?edition=tcm%3A77-400776</a></del> <ins class="ministerial"><a href="http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/publications/re-reference-tables.html?edition=tcm:77-387081" target="_blank">http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/publications/re-reference-tables.html?edition=tcm%3A77-387081</a></ins></p><p> </p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-01-29T12:46:31.667Z","2016-02-11T10:09:03.437Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447815/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447815/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447815/answer","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447815/answer/previousversion/42084","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-01-26","Occupational Money Purchase Schemes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what data his Department holds on the distribution of contributions to defined-contribution pension schemes for each (a) income level and (b) age.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","24178"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447816","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-29","<p>Distributions of deemed contributions to defined-benefit (DB) schemes broken down by income level or age, are not readily available, and have not been previously published as official statistics.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-01-29T12:39:23.853Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447816/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447816/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447816/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-01-26","Occupational Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what data his Department holds on the distribution of deemed contributions to defined-benefit pension schemes for each (a) income level and (b) age.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","24179"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447817","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-29","<p>Department for Work and Pensions does not routinely capture management information on the number of people who have suffered a six-month or longer period of sickness.</p><br />","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-01-29T12:36:01.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447817/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447817/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447817/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-01-26","Health","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of the number of people who have suffered a six-month or longer period of sickness in each of the last five years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","24187"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447818","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-01","<p>Removal of automatic housing support for 18 – 21 year olds, announced in the Summer Budget 2015, will be introduced in April 2017. The Department is liaising with a range of key stakeholders as we develop the detail of the policy. Once this work has been completed we will bring forward detailed proposals.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","24093 ; 24133","2016-02-01T13:16:27.963Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447818/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447818/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447818/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-01-26","Housing Benefit: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what recent assessment he has made of the potential effects of plans to restrict housing benefit for 18 to 21 year olds on those people; and which groups of young people will be exempted from those restrictions.","false","Biography information for Jess Phillips","Birmingham, Yardley","Jess Phillips","24199"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447819","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-01","<p>Removal of automatic housing support for 18 – 21 year olds, announced in the Summer Budget 2015, will be introduced in April 2017. The Department is liaising with a range of key stakeholders as we develop the detail of the policy. Once this work has been completed we will bring forward detailed proposals.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","24093 ; 24199","2016-02-01T13:16:27.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447819/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447819/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447819/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-01-26","Housing Benefit: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, which categories of young people it is his policy will be exempt from the new restrictions to housing benefit eligibility.","false","Biography information for Jess Phillips","Birmingham, Yardley","Jess Phillips","24133"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447820","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-29","<p>The 110 non-complaint cases represent 0.02% of the cases with a current liability as at the quarter ending September 2015.</p><p>Notes</p><ol><li>The percentage figure is rounded to 2 decimal places.</li><li>Cases include those paying via Collection Service and Maintenance Direct.</li><li>The non-compliant case figure was at October 2015.</li><li>The percentage figure is of the number of cases with a current liability as at September 2015 (574,400).</li></ol><br />","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-01-29T09:48:38.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447820/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447820/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447820/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-01-26","Children: Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answers of 23 November 2015 to Questions 16300 and 16301, what proportion of cases with a current liability the 110 non-compliant cases that have been closed as part of the CSA case closure programme represent.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","24142"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447821","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-03","<p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>This Government is committed to maintaining and building on the UK’s position as a leader in the global market for investment in health and life sciences – the UK is the number one destination for life science FDI in Europe, and pharmaceutical exports grew 23% in the first three quarters of 2015. Through the Life Sciences Strategy we are working across Government to improve the UK’s competitiveness to stimulate investment, including by protecting the ring-fenced science budget in real terms and increasing funding in real terms to the Catapults which play a key role in commercialising innovation.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-02-03T17:24:42.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447821/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447821/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447821/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-26","Drugs: Investment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps he is taking to maintain the UK's position as a market for investment by global pharmaceutical companies.","false","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse","24238"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447822","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-03","<p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Our latest estimates show that collective Government support through the Life Science Strategy has stimulated more than £6 billion in new investment by the life sciences industry linked to more than 17,000 new sector jobs. Underpinning this success is the UK’s world class science base and an increasingly strong and informed relationship between our universities and wider life sciences community, which is a key attractor for investment by domestic and overseas companies. Through the Accelerated Access Review the government is making this country a world leading place to design, develop and deploy medical innovations, stimulating investment and creating a stronger NHS.</p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-02-03T17:26:16.63Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447822/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447822/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447822/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-26","Life Sciences: Investment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will make an assessment of the link between government support for UK Life Sciences and pharmaceutical research and development investment in the UK.","false","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse","24239"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447823","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-03","<p>The Student Loans Company (SLC) administers student support for the UK Government and Devolved Administrations. Information on the number of borrowers is published annually by the SLC in the Statistical First Release, <em>Student Loans in England:</em></p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.slc.co.uk/official-statistics/student-loans-debt-and-repayment/england.aspx" target="_blank">http://www.slc.co.uk/official-statistics/student-loans-debt-and-repayment/england.aspx</a></p><p> </p><p>At the end of the financial year 2014-15, there were: (a) 3,810, (b) 27,040, and (c) 112,340, borrowers on post-2012 student loan arrangements who had been domiciled in: (a) Birmingham, Ladywood constituency, (b) the City of Birmingham and (c) the West Midlands, when they applied for financial support.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-02-03T17:34:37.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447823/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447823/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447823/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-26","Students: West Midlands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what estimate he has made of the number of student loan borrowers with post-2012 student loan arrangements in (a) Birmingham, Ladywood constituency, (b) the City of Birmingham and (c) the West Midlands metropolitan county.","false","Biography information for Shabana Mahmood","Birmingham, Ladywood","Shabana Mahmood","24240"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447824","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-03","<p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>This Government recognises that health and life sciences industries are a key source of future growth and is committed through the Life Sciences Strategy to providing a supportive wider business environment in which these industries can flourish, so that the UK can be the best place in the world to develop and launch innovative medicines, technologies and diagnostics. Priorities include: simplifying the adoption of transformative products within the NHS through the Accelerated Access Review; supporting new and growing markets and disruptive technologies – such as digital health and genomics; and working across Government to improve the UK’s competitiveness to stimulate investment and drive export growth. Our latest estimates show collective Government support since the Life Science Strategy launched has stimulated more than £6bn in new investment by the life science industry linked to more than 17,000 new sector jobs.</p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-02-03T17:36:15.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447824/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447824/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447824/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-26","Life Sciences: Industry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps his Department is taking to support the life sciences industry.","false","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse","24275"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447825","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-03","<p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Skills policy is a devolved area so the Devolved Administrations have complete flexibility over how to support businesses in all sectors to ensure there are sufficient skilled workers. In England, our 2020 Vision sets out how we will reach 3 million apprenticeship starts by 2020. We are supporting the growth of apprenticeships in all sectors by working with large and small businesses to begin or expand their programmes, setting new expectations for public sector bodies, and through public procurement.</p><p> </p><p>Employer-led reforms continue to improve the quality of apprenticeships, with employers designing new apprenticeship standards that fully meet their skills needs. Employers in the advanced manufacturing and engineering sector are involved in developing apprenticeship standards in over 30 occupations, including aerospace engineer and manufacturing engineer.</p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-02-03T17:33:06.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447825/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447825/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447825/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-26","Manufacturing Industries: Skilled Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will make an assessment of the implications for his policy on apprenticeships of the finding of the Institution of Mechanical Engineers in its report, Engineered in Britain, published in December 2015, that more than half of manufacturers think that a lack of skilled people is the biggest danger to UK manufacturing.","false","Biography information for Philip Boswell","Coatbridge, Chryston and Bellshill","Phil Boswell","24343"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447826","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-03","<p>My Department has worked with Maritime bodies to increase awareness of the National Minimum Wage (NMW) enforcement options available, including the ACAS helpline and HMRC enforcement operations. The Department for Business, Innovation and Skills is working with the sector to agree specific NMW guidance for seafarers. This guide will provide more information on the UK and International maritime law and raise awareness of enforcement measures in place to help anyone who needs them. The guide will advertise the ACAS helpline. I have also met with the hon Member for Gateshead (Ian Mearnes), Convenor of the RMT, to discuss the enforcement of the NMW and how we can raise awareness of enforcement action further.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","24306","2016-02-03T17:14:25.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447826/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447826/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447826/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-26","Employment: Telephone Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what recent steps he has taken to advertise the ACAS-administered Pay and Work Rights Helpline to seafarers recruited from overseas to work in the UK shipping industry.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","24305"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447827","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-03","<p>My Department has worked with Maritime bodies to increase awareness of the National Minimum Wage (NMW) enforcement options available, including the ACAS helpline and HMRC enforcement operations. The Department for Business, Innovation and Skills is working with the sector to agree specific NMW guidance for seafarers. This guide will provide more information on the UK and International maritime law and raise awareness of enforcement measures in place to help anyone who needs them. The guide will advertise the ACAS helpline. I have also met with the hon Member for Gateshead (Ian Mearnes), Convenor of the RMT, to discuss the enforcement of the NMW and how we can raise awareness of enforcement action further.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","24305","2016-02-03T17:14:26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447827/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447827/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447827/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-26","Shipping: Minimum Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps he is taking to ensure effective enforcement of the National Minimum Wage in the maritime sector.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","24306"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447828","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-09","<p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The following table shows actual spending figures for apprenticeships in England for Financial Years 2010-2014</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>£K</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>FY2010-11</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>FY2011-12</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>FY2012-13</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>FY2013-14</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>FY2014-15</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>16 to18 inclusive</p></td><td><p>744,870</p></td><td><p>758,966</p></td><td><p>670,211</p></td><td><p>717,575</p></td><td><p>783,198</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>19 and over</p></td><td><p>450,880</p></td><td><p>624,602</p></td><td><p>753,886</p></td><td><p>737,022</p></td><td><p>776,573</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>TOTAL</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>1,195,750</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>1,383,568</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>1,424,097</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>1,454,597</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>1,559,771</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Responsibility for the Apprenticeship Programme is shared between the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills which funds adult apprenticeships (19+) and the Department for Education which funds 16-18 year olds.</p><p> </p><p>The apprenticeships levy will put apprenticeship funding on an even more sustainable footing and improve the technical and professional skills of the workforce, which is an important component of productivity.</p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-02-09T17:24:43.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447828/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447828/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447828/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-26","Apprentices: Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how much funding has been allocated to apprenticeships in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Philip Boswell","Coatbridge, Chryston and Bellshill","Phil Boswell","24266"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447829","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-01","<p>Between 1 September 2015 and 27 January 2016 the Department received 441 questions for answer on a named day. Of these 250, or 57%, were answered on that named day.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-02-01T17:01:33.28Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447829/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447829/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447829/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-26","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Written Questions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many and what proportion of his Department's Named Day Questions have been answered on the named day since September 2015.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","24374"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447830","Cabinet Office","false","2016-01-29","<p>Whilst the most recent figures for 2015 have not yet been confirmed, the table below shows numbers of National Citizen Service participants since the programme began in 2011.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Number of NCS Participants</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>8,434</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>26,003</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>39,566</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>57,789</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>To be published in 2016</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>We have ambitious targets for the next three years, on a trajectory to deliver 300,000 participants per year in 2019. We are committed to extending the benefits of NCS to as many young people and communities as possible, by providing a place for every young person who wants one.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2016-01-29T17:07:49.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447830/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447830/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447830/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-01-26","Voluntary Work: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many people have taken part in the National Citizen Service (NCS) in each of the last five years; how many people he estimates will take part in the NCS in the next three years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","24310"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447831","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-29","<p>The Government does not hold its own records on total accumulated pension wealth, only on pension contributions. For the purposes of the Lifetime Allowance, officials have used data from the ONS Wealth and Assets Survey, which includes estimates of pension wealth.</p><br /><p>The Government assessed the effects of changes to the Annual Allowance and Lifetime Allowance by considering how many people would have to reduce their saving in response to these reductions. This methodology was agreed with the OBR.</p><br /><p>The reduction in the Lifetime Allowance will affect only 4% of savers currently approaching retirement. The Lifetime Allowance will be reduced to £1 million from April, but the average pension savings of someone approaching retirement is only £85,000.</p><br /><p>Just 1% of savers make contributions of £40,000 per year, the level of the Annual Allowance since April 2014. The average saver contributes £6,000 per year.</p><br /><p>The introduction of the Tapered Annual Allowance for individuals who earn over £150,000 in April 2016 will impact less than 2% of people saving into a pension.</p><br /><p>The Government laid out its modelling on the effect of changes to the Annual and Lifetime Allowances on pension contributions in its policy costings documents at the March and Summer Budgets 2015.</p><br /><p>For changes to the Lifetime Allowance, the Wealth and Assets Survey was used to estimate pension wealth, and this was projected forward using assumed pension contributions and estimates of the real rate of return on pensions savings taken from the OECD and the Government Actuary’s Department.</p><br /><p>For the Tapered Annual Allowance, modelling used estimates from the Survey of Personal Incomes, HMRC operational data on personal pension contributions, the ONS Annual Survey of Hours and Earnings, and the Occupational Pension Scheme Survey.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","24255 ; 24316","2016-01-29T12:36:49.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447831/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447831/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447831/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-26","Pensions: Tax Allowances","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what information his Department holds on accumulated pension wealth on the lifetime allowance basis.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","24315"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447832","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-29","<p>The Government does not hold its own records on total accumulated pension wealth, only on pension contributions. For the purposes of the Lifetime Allowance, officials have used data from the ONS Wealth and Assets Survey, which includes estimates of pension wealth.</p><br /><p>The Government assessed the effects of changes to the Annual Allowance and Lifetime Allowance by considering how many people would have to reduce their saving in response to these reductions. This methodology was agreed with the OBR.</p><br /><p>The reduction in the Lifetime Allowance will affect only 4% of savers currently approaching retirement. The Lifetime Allowance will be reduced to £1 million from April, but the average pension savings of someone approaching retirement is only £85,000.</p><br /><p>Just 1% of savers make contributions of £40,000 per year, the level of the Annual Allowance since April 2014. The average saver contributes £6,000 per year.</p><br /><p>The introduction of the Tapered Annual Allowance for individuals who earn over £150,000 in April 2016 will impact less than 2% of people saving into a pension.</p><br /><p>The Government laid out its modelling on the effect of changes to the Annual and Lifetime Allowances on pension contributions in its policy costings documents at the March and Summer Budgets 2015.</p><br /><p>For changes to the Lifetime Allowance, the Wealth and Assets Survey was used to estimate pension wealth, and this was projected forward using assumed pension contributions and estimates of the real rate of return on pensions savings taken from the OECD and the Government Actuary’s Department.</p><br /><p>For the Tapered Annual Allowance, modelling used estimates from the Survey of Personal Incomes, HMRC operational data on personal pension contributions, the ONS Annual Survey of Hours and Earnings, and the Occupational Pension Scheme Survey.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","24255 ; 24315","2016-01-29T12:36:50.02Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447832/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447832/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447832/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-26","Pensions: Tax Allowances","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, on what basis his Department assessed the effect of changes to the (a) annual allowance and (b) lifetime allowance on pension contributions.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","24316"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447833","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-01","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) expects to be operating with around 60,000 full time equivalent (FTE) staff on 31 March 2016.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC’s Business Plan for 2016-17 is currently being finalised and will be published by the end of March 2016 on GOV.UK. This will contain estimated FTE figures for 31 March 2017 and future staffing projections.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-02-01T15:43:47.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447833/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447833/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447833/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-26","Revenue and Customs: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the number of full-time equivalent staff at HM Revenue and Customs on 31 March (a) 2016 and (b) 2017.","false","Biography information for Rob Marris","Wolverhampton South West","Rob Marris","24317"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447834","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-03","<p>Initial donations from the sanitary products VAT women’s charities fund totalling £5 million have been made to support The Eve Appeal, SafeLives and Women’s Aid, and The Haven. Further donations and recipients will be announced at Budget 2016, and at future fiscal events. The £15 million annual fund will continue to run over the course of this Parliament or until the UK can apply a zero rate of VAT on sanitary products.</p><p> </p><p>Charities interested in applying should email the Treasury directly at <a href="mailto:Tampontax.Fund@hmtreasury.gsi.gov.uk" target="_blank">Tampontax.Fund@hmtreasury.gsi.gov.uk</a> stating their interest in the fund, including an overview of the nature of their proposal and the amount they are requesting. Following this they will be given further details of the bidding process and the detailed information required.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-02-03T16:03:49.753Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447834/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447834/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447834/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-26","Sanitary Protection: VAT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to paragraph 1.144 of the Spending Review and Autumn Statement 2015, how much of the £15 million annual VAT revenue from female sanitary products has been (a) spent to date and (b) allocated for future spending; by what process the recipients of those funds are determined; and whether he plans a further round of allocations for financial year 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Paula Sherriff","Dewsbury","Paula Sherriff","24344"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447835","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-03","<p>The HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) office at Phoenix House, Oldham was announced for closure in February 2008 as part of HMRC’s earlier Regional Review Programme, and was partially vacated in November 2009 with the majority of staff relocating to Manchester and finally closed in May 2014.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC has not undertaken a separate value for money review on the closure of the office in Oldham. The Change Programme, of which the Regional Review Programme formed part, has been reviewed by the National Audit Office as part of its role to scrutinise public spending for Parliament to assess value for money. The NAO carried out a specific review on cost reduction within HMRC in 2013. The report can be found on the attached link. <a href="https://www.nao.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/HMRC-reducing-cost-full-report.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.nao.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/HMRC-reducing-cost-full-report.pdf</a></p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-02-03T15:58:47.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447835/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447835/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447835/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-26","Revenue and Customs: Greater Manchester","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will publish the value for money review of the relocation of Oldham HM Revenue and Customs Office to Manchester city centre.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","24298"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447836","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-29","<p>Treasury Ministers and officials have meetings with a wide variety of organisations in the public and private sectors as part of the process of policy development and delivery. Details of ministerial and permanent secretary meetings with external organisations on departmental business are published on a quarterly basis and are available at: https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/hmt-ministers-meetings-hospitality-gifts-and-overseas-travel</p><br />","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-01-29T12:41:06.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447836/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447836/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447836/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-26","Housing Benefit: Supported Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what representations he has received from (a) providers of supported housing and (b) organisations representing people with disabilities on the effect of a cap on housing benefit on the provision of supported housing.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","24251"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447837","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-01","<p>The government keeps all tax and welfare policies under review. HM Treasury does not at present have any plans to produce or publish any research on or assessment of basic income schemes.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-02-01T15:29:15.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447837/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447837/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447837/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-26","Welfare State","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what feasibility studies or other assessments of basic income schemes have been carried out by HM Treasury officials since 1990; and if he will place copies of any such studies or assessments in the Library.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","24355"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447838","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-29","<p>The Government does not hold its own records on total accumulated pension wealth, only on pension contributions. For the purposes of the Lifetime Allowance, officials have used data from the ONS Wealth and Assets Survey, which includes estimates of pension wealth.</p><br /><p>The Government assessed the effects of changes to the Annual Allowance and Lifetime Allowance by considering how many people would have to reduce their saving in response to these reductions. This methodology was agreed with the OBR.</p><br /><p>The reduction in the Lifetime Allowance will affect only 4% of savers currently approaching retirement. The Lifetime Allowance will be reduced to £1 million from April, but the average pension savings of someone approaching retirement is only £85,000.</p><br /><p>Just 1% of savers make contributions of £40,000 per year, the level of the Annual Allowance since April 2014. The average saver contributes £6,000 per year.</p><br /><p>The introduction of the Tapered Annual Allowance for individuals who earn over £150,000 in April 2016 will impact less than 2% of people saving into a pension.</p><br /><p>The Government laid out its modelling on the effect of changes to the Annual and Lifetime Allowances on pension contributions in its policy costings documents at the March and Summer Budgets 2015.</p><br /><p>For changes to the Lifetime Allowance, the Wealth and Assets Survey was used to estimate pension wealth, and this was projected forward using assumed pension contributions and estimates of the real rate of return on pensions savings taken from the OECD and the Government Actuary’s Department.</p><br /><p>For the Tapered Annual Allowance, modelling used estimates from the Survey of Personal Incomes, HMRC operational data on personal pension contributions, the ONS Annual Survey of Hours and Earnings, and the Occupational Pension Scheme Survey.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","24315 ; 24316","2016-01-29T12:36:49.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447838/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447838/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447838/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-26","Pensions: Tax Allowances","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what modelling his Department undertakes on the effect on changes to pension contributions of changes to (a) annual allowance and (b) lifetime allowance; and what sources his Department uses for such modelling.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","24255"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447839","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-29","<p>The information is not available.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-01-29T09:26:42.01Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447839/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447839/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447839/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-01-26","Supported Housing: Housing Benefit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of the loss of income to providers of supported housing from a cap on housing benefit at the rate of local housing allowance.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","24250"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447840","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-03","<p>The Government supports longer tenancies, and promotes them through its Model Tenancy Agreement. We have continued to encourage mortgage lenders to permit family friendly tenancies, and the majority have now changed their policies, and permit tenancies of up to two to three years.</p><p>A letter was sent to the Council for Mortgage Lenders on this subject in January 2016, urging them to encourage those lenders who have not changed their policies to do so, and to encourage lenders to promote the benefits of the Model Tenancy Agreement to their landlord customers.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-02-03T13:27:55.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447840/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447840/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447840/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-01-26","Mortgages","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what progress his Department is making on encouraging buy-to-let mortgage lenders to allow longer tenancies in their terms and conditions.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","24354"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447841","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-03","<p>The Build-to-Rent programme has helped to catalyse funding from other sources. Developers are now proceeding with schemes that will deliver over 3,000 homes using alternative finance after having originally made an application to the Fund.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-02-03T13:26:33.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447841/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447841/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447841/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-01-26","Private Rented Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment his Department has made of the effectiveness of round 2 of the Build to Rent scheme in delivering new homes; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Stewart Jackson","Peterborough","Mr Stewart Jackson","24376"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447842","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-29","<p>The information requested is not available.</p><br />","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-01-29T09:29:57.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447842/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447842/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447842/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-01-26","Supported Housing: Housing Benefit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the effect on local authority budgets of people in supported housing not remaining in that housing as a result of a cap on housing benefit at the rate of local housing allowance.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","24256"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447843","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-04","<p>The Troubled Families Programme in the Peterborough City Council area helped produce successful outcomes with 450 troubled families. This was assessed according to whether children were attending school, youth crime and anti-social behaviour had been reduced, and adults from troubled families were helped off out-of-work benefits and into continuous employment.</p><p>Under the provisions of the Welfare Reform and Work Bill, I will be reporting on the progress of the Troubled Families Programme annually.</p>","Tunbridge Wells","Greg Clark",,"2016-02-04T16:10:13.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447843/answer","Biography information for Greg Clark","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447843/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447843/answer","Tunbridge Wells","Greg Clark","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447843/answer/previousversion/42148","Biography information for Greg Clark","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-01-26","Families: Disadvantaged","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the progress made by the Troubled Families initiative in the Peterborough City Council area since 2011; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Stewart Jackson","Peterborough","Mr Stewart Jackson","24329"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447844","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-01-29","<p>The Department does not publish forecasts of house building. It is for local planning authorities to ensure that they plan for the full, objectively assessed housing needs in their area.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-01-29T14:13:52.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447844/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447844/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447844/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-01-26","Housing: Newham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many units of housing he expects to be built in the London borough of Newham in each year to 2020.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","24336"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447845","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-02-03","<p>Once the new broadband USO is in place, Ofcom will monitor its implementation and feedback progress to Government.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-02-03T18:20:09.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447845/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447845/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447845/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-01-26","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how his Department will measure the progress of the roll-out of the broadband universal service obligation.","false","Biography information for Drew Hendry","Inverness, Nairn, Badenoch and Strathspey","Drew Hendry","24268"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447846","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-01-29","<p>Ofcom reported on the operation of the television production sector on 23 December. I am now considering that report, and will make a decision in due course.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","24149","2016-01-29T13:22:44.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447846/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447846/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447846/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-01-26","Broadcasting Programmes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment he has made of the implications for his policies of Ofcom's review of the future regulatory framework of the independent television production sector; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for David Warburton","Somerton and Frome","David Warburton","24328"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447847","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-01-29","<p>The Government is determined to get more girls and women playing sport and to remove any barrier that prevents women and other under-represented groups from taking part in sport and wider physical activity. In December we published a new cross-Departmental strategy for sport and physical activity, 'Sporting Future: A New Strategy for an Active Nation', which sets out a new vision for a successful and active sporting nation.</p><p>While grassroots sport is a devolved matter, we recognise the complicated landscape of reserved and devolved powers around responsibility for sport and physical activity. To help improve co-ordination and sharing of best practice among the the devolved administrations and the UK Government, the 'Sport Cabinet' will be re-established. It will bring together the four sports ministers who represent Scotland, Wales, Northern Ireland and both England and the UK as a whole.</p>","Bexleyheath and Crayford","David Evennett",,"2016-01-29T09:22:37.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447847/answer","Biography information for Sir David Evennett","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447847/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447847/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-01-26","Sports: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if he will discuss with his counterparts in the devolved administrations how to maximise the practical steps being taken across the UK to increase female participation in sports.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","24339"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447848","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-03-10","<p>DCMS secured an excellent settlement in the latest Spending Round that highlights the important contributions our sectors make in job creation, helping grow our economy, and bringing arts and culture to communities across the UK. Arts Council England's overall settlement over the Spending Review period maintains the current resource budget in cash terms - £354,042,000 in 2016/17; £350,724,000 in 2017/8; £357,593,000 in 2018/19 and £359,307,000 in 2019/20.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-03-10T16:57:14.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447848/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447848/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447848/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-01-26","Arts Council England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what his Department's planned expenditure on grant-in-aid to Arts Council England is for (a) 2016-17, (b) 2017-18, (c) 2018-19 and (d) 2019-20.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","24352"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447849","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-02-04","<p>As Good Cause income is dependent on sales, we can not provide precise figures for future forecasts; figures are a guide to likely overall income if sales remain at levels at the time of the review. However, Arts Council England’s annual share of income to the National Lottery Distribution Fund is estimated to be £255 million for each year from 2016/17 to 2019/20.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-02-04T17:13:45.22Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447849/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447849/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447849/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-01-26","Arts Council England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what estimate his Department has made of the income that Arts Council of England will receive from National Lottery funding in (a) 2016-17, (b) 2017-18, (c) 2018-19 and (d) 2019-20.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","24353"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447850","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-03-08","<p>The Chancellor announced on 25 November that DCMS core administration funding will reduce by 20% in real terms over this spending period. This reflects the planned reduction in Broadband Delivery UK administration funding as projects deliver their targets on time, as well as further efficiency savings which will be made across the Department over the Spending Review period.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-03-08T17:13:07.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447850/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447850/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447850/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-01-26","Department for Culture, Media and Sport: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what estimate he has made of the reduction in staff numbers in his Department needed to meet the efficiency and reform savings announced in the Spending Review and Autumn Statement 2015 for the 2015-16 financial year and in each of the next five years.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","24349"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447851","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-02-04","<p>I and my officials continue to have an ongoing dialogue with the BBC regarding the content and process of the BBC Charter Review.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-02-04T11:21:48.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447851/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447851/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447851/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-01-26","BBC: Royal Charters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what discussions he has had with the BBC on an extension of the current BBC Charter period by order of the Queen in Council.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","24351"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447852","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-02-05","<p>Broadband Delivery UK’s (BDUK) Superfast Broadband Programme remains on track to achieve 90% superfast broadband coverage within the next few months, and 95% by December 2017. In addition, the Government's intention to implement a new broadband Universal Service Obligation will give people the legal right to request at 10Mbps connection, no matter where they live, by the end of this Parliament.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-02-05T16:12:35.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447852/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447852/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447852/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-01-26","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what estimate his Department has made of the proportion of households that will have access to superfast broadband in (a) 2016-17, (b) 2017-18, (c) 2018-19 and (d) 2019-20.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","24345"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447853","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-02-09","<p>The inter-ministerial group on tourism meets quarterly. The first meeting was held on 16th September 2015 and Ministers will meet again in February. Membership is composed of the following Departments, and attendance is subject to the agenda for the meeting:</p><p> </p><ul><li>DCMS</li></ul><p> </p><ul><li>BIS</li></ul><p> </p><ul><li>Home Office</li></ul><p> </p><ul><li>DCLG</li></ul><p> </p><ul><li>DfT</li></ul><p> </p><ul><li>HMT</li></ul><p> </p><p>DEFRA.</p>","Bexleyheath and Crayford","David Evennett",,"2016-02-09T13:36:37.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447853/answer","Biography information for Sir David Evennett","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447853/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447853/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-01-26","Tourism Ministerial Group","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, on what dates the inter-Ministerial group on tourism has met; and who is a member of that group.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","24346"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447854","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-29","<p>The number of apprenticeship starts in the ‘Leisure, Travel and Tourism’ Sector Subject Area by academic year are shown in Table 1.</p><p> </p><p>Table 1 - Apprenticeship starts, 2010/11 to 2014/15</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Sector Subject Area</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2010/11</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2011/12</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2012/13</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013/14</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014/15</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Leisure, Travel and Tourism</p></td><td><p>21,590</p></td><td><p>19,770</p></td><td><p>14,360</p></td><td><p>11,350</p></td><td><p>13,070</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>We are committed to reaching 3 million apprenticeship starts in England by 2020. There were 2.4 million apprenticeship starts over the previous Parliament.</p><p> </p><p>Apprenticeships are paid jobs and their availability is dependent on employers offering opportunities and hiring apprentices.</p><p> </p><p>The figures in the table are found in the apprenticeship data library:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/493777/apprenticeships-starts-by-geography-learner-demographics-and-sector-subject-area.xls" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/493777/apprenticeships-starts-by-geography-learner-demographics-and-sector-subject-area.xls</a></p><p> </p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-02-29T09:30:41.193Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447854/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447854/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447854/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-26","Apprentices: Tourism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many apprenticeships were created in the tourism sector in (a) 2010-11, (b) 2011-12, (c) 2012-13 and (d) 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","24347"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447855","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-02-24","<p>Satellite broadband can deliver download speeds of 10Mbps and above and upload speeds of 5Mbps. The subsidised offer to meet the Universal Service Commitment gives a first year only cost for a basic package of up to £400. This will make available an affordable basic broadband service to those premises unable to get a speed of at least 2Mbps. The total number of premises eligible for the universal service commitment subsidy had been substantially reduced, from around 11% in 2010 to around 1% by the end of 2015, as a result of roll-out superfast broadband by the commercial sector and through publicly-funded programmes.</p><p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-02-24T13:52:23.53Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447855/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447855/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/447855/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-01-26","Broadband: Rural Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment his Department has made of the adequacy of satellite broadband for serving rural areas; and what steps his Department is taking to ensure parity of service and cost with other types of broadband supply.","false","Biography information for Drew Hendry","Inverness, Nairn, Badenoch and Strathspey","Drew Hendry","24214"
